00:14:51.920 --> 00:14:55.160
We're talking about many
Amazon's that overlap,

00:14:55.160 --> 00:14:57.000
expand and contract over time.

00:15:02.390 --> 00:15:04.920
So let's talk about
the myth of the Amazon.

00:15:06.300 --> 00:15:08.920
As Neil White had pointed
out the very fact

00:15:08.920 --> 00:15:10.660
that we call it the Amazon
should tell us something.

00:15:10.660 --> 00:15:14.580
And the very elusiveness
of Amazonia on the ground

00:15:14.580 --> 00:15:17.430
as an entity that can't be bounded.

00:15:17.430 --> 00:15:23.000 position:56%
Or as I would put it, our insistence
that such an Amazon must exist.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:26.430
Makes it a place that
must be imagined.

00:15:27.560 --> 00:15:31.560
Let's look at how we've imagined
it in contemporary times.

00:15:34.190 --> 00:15:36.030
The largest rain forest
on Earth has been touted

00:15:36.030 --> 00:15:37.540
as the lungs of the world.

00:15:37.540 --> 00:15:41.260
A global air conditioner and
as an essential carbon sink.

00:15:41.260 --> 00:15:43.940
Of those global ecosystems
services Amazonia has been said

00:15:43.940 --> 00:15:47.800
to provide only the
last seems to be true.

00:15:47.800 --> 00:15:51.000
And apparently diminishing.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:53.230
The other two functions are myths.

00:15:53.230 --> 00:15:56.290
And apparently the need
for myths is great.

00:15:56.290 --> 00:15:59.430
As far as Amazonia is
concerned at least.

00:15:59.430 --> 00:16:02.610
Mythologies arise, circulate,
diminish and often come back

00:16:02.610 --> 00:16:06.880
to haunt us and they will today.

00:16:06.880 --> 00:16:10.460
Regardless of whether these myths
are true, they serve a function.

00:16:10.460 --> 00:16:14.240
They tell us today why we should
care about a place that seems

00:16:14.240 --> 00:16:19.490
so very very far away in
both space and in time.

00:16:19.490 --> 00:16:23.410 position:56%
Thanks to these myths we have an
awareness that Amazonia is important

00:16:23.410 --> 00:16:26.840
to the future of the
Earth in some way.

00:16:26.840 --> 00:16:29.010
Whether it has to do with
environmental preservation,

00:16:29.010 --> 00:16:31.550
climate change, conscious
consumerism

00:16:31.550 --> 00:16:35.730
or on occasion indigenous
or human rights.

00:16:35.730 --> 00:16:37.440
These particular myths
also tell us something

00:16:37.440 --> 00:16:40.000
about our ideas about Amazonia.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:44.300
That it's still possible to locate
the magnificent and the horrifying

00:16:44.300 --> 00:16:47.360
in a place we have known
for nearly 500 years.

00:16:47.360 --> 00:16:50.080
Known but not understood.

00:16:52.840 --> 00:16:56.680
Occasionally I do a search on
the internet for the Amazon.

00:16:56.680 --> 00:17:01.580
And after I've filtered through all
the search results for the site,

00:17:01.580 --> 00:17:04.170
I usually come up with
images like these.

00:17:04.170 --> 00:17:08.740
People advertising it's nature or
people calling for it's salvation.

00:17:08.740 --> 00:17:13.300 position:56%
Rarely do we see pictures of people.

00:17:13.300 --> 00:17:15.320
But people made the Amazon.

00:17:15.320 --> 00:17:20.500
So we need to rethink this.

00:17:20.500 --> 00:17:23.300
And when I first traveled to
the Amazon, even though I knew

00:17:23.300 --> 00:17:26.430 position:56%
that I was going to an archeological
dig and I knew that I was going

00:17:26.430 --> 00:17:28.870
to be excavating things
that people did,

00:17:28.870 --> 00:17:31.940 position:56%
I still had these images in my head.

00:17:31.940 --> 00:17:36.010
And I think a lot of us
do or a lot of us hope to.

00:17:36.010 --> 00:17:38.850
And that's something to explore
and that's something that's kind

00:17:38.850 --> 00:17:40.150
of beyond the scope of what I do.

00:17:40.150 --> 00:17:42.770
But I just want to
throw that out there.

00:17:42.770 --> 00:17:46.370
I remember thinking, on the
plane, I'm going to the Amazon.

00:17:46.370 --> 00:17:48.200
I'm going to the Amazon.

00:17:48.200 --> 00:17:50.930
How cool is that.

00:17:50.930 --> 00:17:54.490 position:56%
So I want to talk about that
Amazon, that mystical mythical place

00:17:54.490 --> 00:17:57.620
that we learn about in school
and through film and even

00:17:57.620 --> 00:17:59.370
through reputable news outlets.

00:17:59.370 --> 00:18:02.000
How did this place come to be?

00:18:06.050 --> 00:18:08.720
Even on the map the Amazon
was discovered and labeled

00:18:08.720 --> 00:18:10.870
as the sweet sea in 1500.

00:18:10.870 --> 00:18:13.710
It wasn't until February of 1541

00:18:13.710 --> 00:18:16.050
that people understood
it as a river.

00:18:16.050 --> 00:18:18.710
It was in that month
that Gonzalo Pizarro,

00:18:18.710 --> 00:18:23.500 position:56%
then governor of [inaudible] a
province located in modern day Peru,

00:18:23.500 --> 00:18:26.560
went in search of the fabled land
of cinnamon, [foreign language].

00:18:26.560 --> 00:18:32.040
There he hoped to extract at
a fraction of a cost a spice

00:18:32.040 --> 00:18:35.990
that could be valued on a par with
the coveted Sri Lankan cinnamon.

00:18:35.990 --> 00:18:39.660
And in the enthusiasm of the
day, Pizarro saw the new world

00:18:39.660 --> 00:18:40.960
as the land of opportunity.

00:18:40.960 --> 00:18:43.400
And sought not only
the land of cinnamon

00:18:43.400 --> 00:18:47.590
but also the fabled
city Manoa or El Dorado.

00:18:47.590 --> 00:18:53.980
El Dorado is one of the names
of the fabled city of gold.

00:18:53.980 --> 00:18:59.000
Also known simply as Dorado,
Manoa del Dorado, Parime, Patiti,

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:03.310
the lake of gold, the castle of
gold and several other names.

00:19:03.310 --> 00:19:07.990
El Dorado features in discovery and
scientific narratives for centuries

00:19:07.990 --> 00:19:09.820
as late as the 18th century.

00:19:09.820 --> 00:19:16.730
So what we're looking at here,
is an archeological object.

00:19:16.730 --> 00:19:21.860
That's attributed to the muisca
people and they were known

00:19:21.860 --> 00:19:28.980 position:56%
in Colombia apparently legend has
it that the king would adorn himself

00:19:28.980 --> 00:19:32.670
in gold annually as part
of a renewal ceremony

00:19:32.670 --> 00:19:34.600
and then he would bath in a lake.

00:19:34.600 --> 00:19:38.700 position:56%
And many who will think that this is
the origin of the myth of El Dorado

00:19:38.700 --> 00:19:42.510
but as you'll see El Dorado
gets located much further away,

00:19:42.510 --> 00:19:44.000
not 50 years later.

00:19:50.790 --> 00:19:53.850
When I talk about El Dorado,
I'm also indexing other kinds

00:19:53.850 --> 00:19:56.820
of narratives of treasure and I
know that I have green hell here,

00:19:56.820 --> 00:19:59.410
that should really say
green hell or paradise.

00:19:59.410 --> 00:20:03.090
Because depending on your
perspective it could be either.

00:20:03.090 --> 00:20:05.120
So I'm talking about the
idea of an earthly paradise

00:20:05.120 --> 00:20:07.460
which Europeans were also
seeking in the new world.

00:20:07.460 --> 00:20:10.750
I'm talking about our Garden
of Eden, a land of plenty

00:20:10.750 --> 00:20:14.460
or opportunity or in the
words of Voltaire's Candide,

00:20:14.460 --> 00:20:17.890
the best of all possible worlds.

00:20:17.890 --> 00:20:20.680
After ten months of
fruitless voyaging Pizarro

00:20:20.680 --> 00:20:24.840 position:56%
and his crew found themselves
entering an unknown forested valley.

00:20:24.840 --> 00:20:28.230
Hungry and dangerously low on
supplies, the party stopped,

00:20:28.230 --> 00:20:32.030
sending captain Francisco de
Orellana down the Coca River.

00:20:32.030 --> 00:20:34.470
With a small crew in
search of salvation.

00:20:34.470 --> 00:20:39.960
The small crew was completely
unprepared for the size and force

00:20:39.960 --> 00:20:42.460
of the [inaudible] or so
they would later report.

00:20:42.460 --> 00:20:46.600
This along with their utter
ignorance of the terrain,

00:20:46.600 --> 00:20:48.800
a green hell by some accounts.

00:20:48.800 --> 00:20:51.660
Combined to make a
return journey impossible.

00:20:51.660 --> 00:20:55.220
Instead Orellana and his men
journeyed down river to the east.

00:20:55.220 --> 00:20:59.320 position:56%
Completing the first fully
recorded decent of the Amazon River.

00:20:59.320 --> 00:21:02.340
And I think it's crucial
here that Orellana

00:21:02.340 --> 00:21:05.820
and his men were not planning
to do this and didn't know

00:21:05.820 --> 00:21:07.290
where they were going to end up.

00:21:07.290 --> 00:21:10.650
Because the narrative that
we get from the journals,

00:21:10.650 --> 00:21:15.470 position:56%
even though it falls in the genre of
survival literature, is free of some

00:21:15.470 --> 00:21:21.230
of the ethnological thinking,
protoethnological thinking

00:21:21.230 --> 00:21:24.260
that later structures
narratives of this place.

00:21:24.260 --> 00:21:26.970
It would be another 100
years before anybody was able

00:21:26.970 --> 00:21:29.190
to complete the journey and it
was done in the opposite direction

00:21:29.190 --> 00:21:34.980
and the narrative that we get
then isn't June 21st we stop

00:21:34.980 --> 00:21:37.230
for food, people were friendly.

00:21:37.230 --> 00:21:41.350
It sounds more like, well
these are the people,

00:21:41.350 --> 00:21:43.690
these are their customs,
this is how they eat.

00:21:43.690 --> 00:21:49.180
And so instantly the Amazon, that
is a place the size of Europe,

00:21:49.180 --> 00:21:51.730
is reduced to a single
point in time.

00:21:51.730 --> 00:21:55.830
And all of the people that live
in it and all of the landscapes,

00:21:55.830 --> 00:21:59.290
are equalized and this
is what sticks.

00:22:00.540 --> 00:22:05.090 position:56%
The term green hell by the way comes
from a narrative by a historian,

00:22:05.090 --> 00:22:09.010
some say a very well,
I would say to sort

00:22:09.010 --> 00:22:13.750
