the longer people have
inhabited that space.

00:45:29.280 --> 00:45:32.160
There's no correlation in
terms of inches or centimeters,

00:45:32.160 --> 00:45:36.380
depth and time but, something
that I think, that's about 50

00:45:36.380 --> 00:45:40.970
or 60 centimeters deep is probably
a very long term occupation

00:45:40.970 --> 00:45:42.930
and when we have hiatus's
we now understand

00:45:42.930 --> 00:45:45.120
that there are different kinds
of soils that intervenes,

00:45:45.120 --> 00:45:48.050
so that is a continuous occupation.

00:45:48.050 --> 00:45:50.230
And I'm going to show you the site
that I worked for my dissertation

00:45:50.230 --> 00:45:52.260
and it only has about
20 centimeters of soil

00:45:52.260 --> 00:45:54.460
and I think we're looking
at 800 years.

00:45:54.460 --> 00:45:58.000
So, this site and I think
is [foreign language].

00:45:58.000 --> 00:46:01.240
We know we're looking at something
that started around 500 BC

00:46:01.240 --> 00:46:06.580
and went right up until
just about contact.

00:46:06.580 --> 00:46:08.610
Stability is the other thing.

00:46:08.610 --> 00:46:11.180
So not only are these
soils more nutrient-rich

00:46:11.180 --> 00:46:13.030
but the can be farmed
for longer periods.

00:46:13.030 --> 00:46:18.670
So even if you clear cut and do a
monoculture on a Terra Preta soil

00:46:18.670 --> 00:46:21.790
which isn't recommended, you
can still farm that soil for up

00:46:21.790 --> 00:46:23.940
to ten years, opposed
to two to three.

00:46:23.940 --> 00:46:25.380
Sometimes people stretch it to five

00:46:25.380 --> 00:46:27.860
but they're really not
getting very much return

00:46:27.860 --> 00:46:31.990
for their labor when they do that.

00:46:31.990 --> 00:46:37.230
So, at the top, on the
right, is one of the densest,

00:46:37.230 --> 00:46:39.780
darkest Terra Preta
sites that I have worked

00:46:39.780 --> 00:46:41.430
on in the central Amazon.

00:46:41.430 --> 00:46:46.750
It is I believe at least
30 hectares in size,

00:46:46.750 --> 00:46:50.490
they're are very large mounds
some of which are funerary,

00:46:50.490 --> 00:46:53.380
some of which we haven't
quite understood yet.

00:46:53.380 --> 00:46:55.000
And if you look at the bottom

00:46:55.000 --> 00:46:57.540
that site [foreign language]
has been farmed in this way

00:46:57.540 --> 00:47:01.630
with several monocultures
for over 25 years.

00:47:01.630 --> 00:47:06.320
I will say that we know that
the current owner does use soil

00:47:06.320 --> 00:47:07.630
amendments but the advantage is

00:47:07.630 --> 00:47:09.880
that they don't get
washed into the river.

00:47:09.880 --> 00:47:15.550
Which is what usually happens if
you use NPK or potash those sorts

00:47:15.550 --> 00:47:18.170
of things on regular
Amazonian soils,

00:47:18.170 --> 00:47:21.130
so another bonus for
the environment.

00:47:21.130 --> 00:47:26.240
So, why do we care about, what
do I care about Terra Preta,

00:47:26.240 --> 00:47:29.000
I think archaeologically
there's lots of reasons to care.

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:32.530
They emerge all across the
Amazon, very quickly it seems

00:47:32.530 --> 00:47:35.900
to be phenomenon that spreads from
one end of the Amazon to the other

00:47:35.900 --> 00:47:39.260
in the space of a couple
hundred years.

00:47:39.260 --> 00:47:44.950
By about 1100 AD, there are massive
sites with palisades and earthworks

00:47:44.950 --> 00:47:49.640
at several of the major
crossroads, so we have a technology

00:47:49.640 --> 00:47:51.960
that has spread and yet
we have different kinds

00:47:51.960 --> 00:47:54.860
of ceramic traditions
which indicates different,

00:47:54.860 --> 00:47:59.430
at the very least different
stylistic ideas or creative trends

00:47:59.430 --> 00:48:01.550
and potentially different
ethnicities if you look

00:48:01.550 --> 00:48:03.870
at the distances on a map.

00:48:03.870 --> 00:48:05.660
It's not absurd to
think that we're talking

00:48:05.660 --> 00:48:08.930
about different ethnicities
using the same sets of practices.

00:48:08.930 --> 00:48:13.280
So what it represents is the
tremendous change in the way

00:48:13.280 --> 00:48:16.090
that humans are relating
to the environment.

00:48:16.090 --> 00:48:17.680
And one of the key
questions that people have is,

00:48:17.680 --> 00:48:19.290
well did they know
what they were doing?

00:48:19.290 --> 00:48:23.930
And so it's something that I've
been researching and I think

00:48:23.930 --> 00:48:27.030
that the best answer is
that initially they didn't

00:48:27.030 --> 00:48:28.770
and at some point they
figured it out.

00:48:28.770 --> 00:48:32.600
Because there are some groups in
the Amazon today that make a sort

00:48:32.600 --> 00:48:35.120
of Terra Preta to use as
gardens intentionally.

00:48:35.120 --> 00:48:37.880
Some of them are indigenous
and some of them are what we

00:48:37.880 --> 00:48:40.130
in Brazil call traditional
farming groups

00:48:40.130 --> 00:48:43.500
which is an officially recognized
government category of people

00:48:43.500 --> 00:48:46.270 position:56%
that have been inhabiting the
Amazon for a certain number of years

00:48:46.270 --> 00:48:49.040
and have a different way of
interacting with each other

00:48:49.040 --> 00:48:51.800
and with Brazilian civil society.

00:48:51.800 --> 00:48:56.030
Then Brazilians would but they
aren't necessarily indigenous

00:48:56.030 --> 00:49:00.680
because of shifting populations
and there's a lot going on there

00:49:00.680 --> 00:49:03.750
but let's just say multiethnic
communities that live

00:49:03.750 --> 00:49:07.760
in the forest using some
traditional practices and some

00:49:07.760 --> 00:49:09.060
of which might have been learned

00:49:09.060 --> 00:49:12.940
from indigenous populations
or a throop heredity.

00:49:12.940 --> 00:49:18.110
I'm interested in how
these things were formed

00:49:18.110 --> 00:49:19.980
at the level the individual.

00:49:19.980 --> 00:49:23.600
Because I think that if we can
find out how people were able

00:49:23.600 --> 00:49:28.030 position:56%
to make the soil then, it
shouldn't be that hard to replicate.

00:49:28.030 --> 00:49:30.580
It is hard to figure
out how they did it.

00:49:30.580 --> 00:49:35.530
And so what I did, was I
appealed to soil science.

00:49:35.530 --> 00:49:42.790
And I also started studying the
way that, that sites were made

00:49:42.790 --> 00:49:45.770
in the present, so as
people inhabit a space,

00:49:45.770 --> 00:49:47.640
what are the kinds of
things that happen?

00:49:47.640 --> 00:49:51.340
What is the evidence of these
everyday repeated actions

00:49:51.340 --> 00:49:53.320
which we call practices?

00:49:53.320 --> 00:49:57.920
And one of the things that one
of my mentors pointed out is

00:49:57.920 --> 00:50:01.000
that these earth ovens, in
this case it's a brick oven

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:02.660
but usually they're earth ovens.

00:50:02.660 --> 00:50:06.830
That people use create a
certain kind of charcoal,

00:50:06.830 --> 00:50:09.540
that's a really important
ingredient in Terra Preta.

00:50:09.540 --> 00:50:13.010
And so that was the first thing
that I noticed that made me think

00:50:13.010 --> 00:50:14.720
that maybe we should be
studying more than the soil

00:50:14.720 --> 00:50:16.970
but also the things
that are in the soil.

00:50:16.970 --> 00:50:18.960
So normally a soil
science will take,

00:50:18.960 --> 00:50:22.980
soil scientist will take a soil
sample and grind it up and put

00:50:22.980 --> 00:50:24.880
into a machine and analyze it.

00:50:24.880 --> 00:50:28.040
And what I did with a host
of undergraduate students,

00:50:28.040 --> 00:50:30.910
there were more than 20
people helping me in the lab,

00:50:30.910 --> 00:50:34.400
was we didn't crush the
samples, we separated everything

00:50:34.400 --> 00:50:36.720
and we analyzed all the little
bits of the things that were

00:50:36.720 --> 00:50:39.910
in these soils to try to
understand what were the things

00:50:39.910 --> 00:50:43.550 position:56%
that contributed to the formation of
Terra Preta and what are the things

00:50:43.550 --> 00:50:46.850
that told us what people
were doing at any given time

00:50:46.850 --> 00:50:49.540
on a particular piece of a site.

00:50:49.540 --> 00:50:54.170
And we're talking I was looking, I
was comparing areas about the size

00:50:54.170 --> 00:51:00.060
of this room, so medium to
large house areas to each other.

00:51:00.060 --> 00:51:03.740
And so in addition to looking
at tiny pieces of charcoal

00:51:03.740 --> 00:51:07.440 position:56%
or charred plant remains we also
ended up looking at tiny tiny pieces

00:51:07.440 --> 00:51:11.270
of ceramics or burnt clay which
might have come from ovens.

00:51:11.270 --> 00:51:13.880
They would've looked
different from this one but,

00:51:13.880 --> 00:51:17.790
we've excavated some things that
look a little bit like earth ovens.

00:51:17.790 --> 00:51:21.320
Moving right along bio-char is
the most important ingredient

00:51:21.320 --> 00:51:23.760
for Terra Preta because
it's very very stable.

00:51:23.760 --> 00:51:26.260
And it also holds onto
other kinds of nutrients.

00:51:26.260 --> 00:51:29.760
If you put bio-char together
with little pieces of bone,

00:51:29.760 --> 00:51:33.720
appetite then you get
an extremely strong bond

00:51:33.720 --> 00:51:36.350
that makes these soils
even more fertile,

00:51:36.350 --> 00:51:38.770
so it's important not only
people were burning things

00:51:38.770 --> 00:51:40.250
but they were cooking.

00:51:40.250 --> 00:51:42.000
Right or that they
were burning garbage

00:51:42.000 --> 00:51:45.550
that contained animal remains,
probably cooking would've happened

00:51:45.550 --> 00:51:49.580
in the unintentional scenario
and the burning garbage

00:51:49.580 --> 00:51:51.870
with animal remains in
the intentional scenario.

00:51:51.870 --> 00:51:54.160
Right so initially people
would've figured it out

00:51:54.160 --> 00:51:58.430
and then they would've started
doing the intentional burning.

00:51:58.430 --> 00:52:03.870
So I'm looking, this is from
my friend Morgan Schmidt's work

00:52:03.870 --> 00:52:06.530
with the Kuikuru Indians
in upper Xingu,

00:52:06.530 --> 00:52:11.090
they make middens intentionally,
they cultivate them in the sense

00:52:11.090 --> 00:52:14.150
that they order the way
that they dispose of garbage

00:52:14.150 --> 00:52:19.430 position:56%
and then they will use certain parts
of the middens as gardens depending

00:52:19.430 --> 00:52:23.690
on how long they've
been sort of simmering.

00:52:23.690 --> 00:52:27.460
And so here we have banana trees
and lemon trees and lime trees,

00:52:27.460 --> 00:52:30.540
things that wouldn't be
growing on Amazonian soils,

00:52:30.540 --> 00:52:32.370
growing right in peoples backyards.

00:52:32.370 --> 00:52:35.750
Very quickly this is the village,
the orange blobs are houses

00:52:35.750 --> 00:52:40.960
and the things behind them are the
middens, the mounds of dark earth

00:52:40.960 --> 00:52:43.830
that people use for gardens.

00:52:43.830 --> 00:52:47.440
So in the central Amazon,
there's lots of beautiful pottery.

00:52:47.440 --> 00:52:55.860
I did a study like this at a
site that consisted of 12 mounds

00:52:55.860 --> 00:52:57.320
that we thought were houses.

00:52:57.320 --> 00:52:59.810
We excavated them and we found
out that did seem [inaudible]

00:52:59.810 --> 00:53:05.840
to be constructed underneath the
platform which is the clay floor

00:53:05.840 --> 00:53:08.050
that has the horizontal lines.

00:53:08.050 --> 00:53:10.890
Is a very charcoal rich soil
which I initially thought would be

00:53:10.890 --> 00:53:13.800
like a Terra Preta but
upon analysis realized

00:53:13.800 --> 00:53:15.360
that that was a garden soil.

00:53:15.360 --> 00:53:17.110
Some of the houses had gardens
underneath them and some

00:53:17.110 --> 00:53:20.380
of the houses had other
houses underneath them.

00:53:20.380 --> 00:53:23.130
Plotting this spatially.

00:53:23.130 --> 00:53:26.240 position:56%
I'm sorry to move so fast I get a
sequence of occupation so we started

00:53:26.240 --> 00:53:29.970
with one house, that house
eventually sprouted other houses

00:53:29.970 --> 00:53:33.040
and these houses were starting
to be built on platforms.

00:53:33.040 --> 00:53:35.230
We're not exactly sure why yet.

00:53:35.230 --> 00:53:38.290
But eventually the entire landscape

00:53:38.290 --> 00:53:40.500
and this is a circumscribed
peninsula

00:53:40.500 --> 00:53:43.350
that was entirely taken
up by houses.

00:53:43.350 --> 00:53:45.150
Right up to the flood line.

00:53:45.150 --> 00:53:48.450
And so what happens when you
circumscribe people on a piece

00:53:48.450 --> 00:53:52.170 position:56%
of land and you're depositing all of
your garbage next to your houses is

00:53:52.170 --> 00:53:56.150
that you get very very
rich soils, very quickly.

00:53:56.150 --> 00:53:59.750
And so I recently published
an article that demonstrates

00:53:59.750 --> 00:54:02.390
that this is how the soils
were transformed suddenly

00:54:02.390 --> 00:54:06.380
through a combination of population
growth and circumscription.

00:54:06.380 --> 00:54:08.470
They overwhelmed the ecosystem

00:54:08.470 --> 00:54:14.400
and transformed what would
have been a very sterile soil

00:54:14.400 --> 00:54:16.750
into a very productive soil.

00:54:16.750 --> 00:54:20.300
This demonstrates that
people were instrumental

00:54:20.300 --> 00:54:23.840 position:56%
in instigating ecological change but
that in this case they didn't seem

00:54:23.840 --> 00:54:27.120
to be doing it on purpose.

00:54:27.120 --> 00:54:31.620
That they were there for several
hundred years, so I don't know

00:54:31.620 --> 00:54:35.170 position:56%
if you caught the chronology but
we're going from about 300 to 500 AD

00:54:35.170 --> 00:54:38.060
to 800 AD, so that's 500 years.

00:54:38.060 --> 00:54:40.700
And that they were investing
in constructing this landscape

00:54:40.700 --> 00:54:42.290
in a particular way
in spite of the fact

00:54:42.290 --> 00:54:44.880
that they were sacrificing
their farmland.

00:54:44.880 --> 00:54:47.810
And so evidently farmland
wasn't terribly important.

00:54:47.810 --> 00:54:50.880 position:56%
So if you think about the way
people occupied space then and think

00:54:50.880 --> 00:54:54.000
about the way people occupy space
now, we might be able to come

00:54:54.000 --> 00:54:58.090
up with better strategies
for managing the Amazon.

00:54:58.090 --> 00:55:00.550
Very quickly going back to
the picture of the village,

00:55:00.550 --> 00:55:01.950
what I want to emphasize
is that as long

00:55:01.950 --> 00:55:04.350
as someone is inhabiting this
space, they're going to be invested

00:55:04.350 --> 00:55:06.680
in thinking about how
to make it better.

00:55:06.680 --> 00:55:10.750
As long as were just using it
and extracting things from it,

00:55:10.750 --> 00:55:13.070
for the purposes of
the outside world,

00:55:13.070 --> 00:55:14.850
then we have no chance
of preserving it.

00:55:14.850 --> 00:55:17.690
So thinking about the Amazon
as a global carbon sink,

00:55:17.690 --> 00:55:20.710
might help in the short run but
isn't really particularly helpful

00:55:20.710 --> 00:55:23.210
in thinking about how
we inhabit the Amazon.

00:55:23.210 --> 00:55:27.100
I don't know whether I should
tell everybody to go live there,

00:55:27.100 --> 00:55:30.740
probably not, but I think that
the solution is the project

00:55:30.740 --> 00:55:35.510
that I'm running now or one
potential solution is to work

00:55:35.510 --> 00:55:38.630
with communities independently

00:55:38.630 --> 00:55:41.890
to see how they manage their
landscapes, see what we can offer

00:55:41.890 --> 00:55:45.940 position:56%
in terms of archaeological
evidence, archaeological narratives,

00:55:45.940 --> 00:55:51.110
tactics to try to help them
create a better management system

00:55:51.110 --> 00:55:55.330
so that their growing
populations can be well articulated

00:55:55.330 --> 00:55:57.850
with this very complex ecosystem.

00:55:57.850 --> 00:56:00.600
That doesn't respond well
to [inaudible] cultural.

00:56:00.600 --> 00:56:06.410
So, all that being said,
thank you to all of the people

00:56:06.410 --> 00:56:09.210
that made this possible
including all of you.

00:56:09.210 --> 00:56:12.050
And I'm through.

